# Project Memory And Instructions

## 0. Role

This file is the master for the {{PROJECT_NAME}} Project Instructions text and the record of how Instructions are kept in sync. This framework **does not use Project Memory**: the docs tree under `docs/` is the single source of truth, gated by `make docs-check`. There is no Memory drift ritual and no `[Memory]` candidate to emit.

## 1. Instructions Only

| Type | Include | Exclude | Update actor |
|---|---|---|---|
| Project Instructions | stable startup protocol, language policy, path-variable rule, docs-consistency rule | volatile {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} state, numbers, {{ANALYSIS_RECORD_LABEL}} history (those live in docs/) | {{USER_NAME}} pastes; the {{ROLE_TERM}} only provides candidate text |

## 2. Current Instructions Candidate

This block is the current candidate for the Claude Project Instructions. It is mirrored byte-identically in `docs/entrypoint.md` section 2; the docs consistency guard enforces that both blocks match. The rendered, paste-ready copy is also written to `project-instructions.txt` at the repo root by init.

```text
<!-- include: _fragments/project-instructions.txt -->
```

## 3. Update Triggers

Provide a new Instructions candidate when any of these change: the startup protocol, the path-variable rule, the chat/docs language policy, or the docs-consistency requirement. Day-to-day research state never goes into Instructions; it lives in the docs tree.

## 4. How To Present A Change

The {{ROLE_TERM}} presents Instructions changes as either the full replacement text or a minimal diff, clearly marked, for {{USER_NAME}} to paste into the Claude Project settings. The {{ROLE_TERM}} states what changed and why in one or two lines.

## 5. Forbidden

- Do not claim the {{ROLE_TERM}} updated the Project Instructions; only {{USER_NAME}} can paste them.
- Do not call any memory-write tool; this framework does not use Project Memory.
- Do not let the two mirror blocks (this file section 2 and `docs/entrypoint.md` section 2) drift; edit them together and run `make docs-check`.
